eA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="glife"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Living/Lifestyle</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gweb"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Top of the News</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Commentary; Facebook privacy scandal: A wake-up call for social media users</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>I have a daughter studying in a primary school in the central part of Singapore. Plus I like to shop for baby stuff such as diapers and toys.</Para><Para>All it took was a couple of hours online for Mr Ryan Flores, a researcher at cloud security solutions firm Trend Micro - and a casual contact whom I've not shared these details with - to dig up this profile of me by tracking my social media footprints.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>This is despite me being selective about whom I add on Facebook, keeping my profile page sparse and limiting most posts to "friends only".</Para><Para>Mr Flores used Socialnet, which costs US$8,000 (S$10,500), to mine my data across different social media - including Facebook, Twitter, Foursquare and Skype. But free online tools, such as Graphs.tips and StalkScan, do an equally decent data-mining job.</Para><Para>Using Socialnet, Mr Flores was able to list the groups, pages and people I've liked and followed on Facebook, allowing him to start to build a profile of me.</Para><Para>For instance, I liked Singapore politician Yaacob Ibrahim and the pages of Pampers, Lovera Collection and Nook and Cranny Living. He was able to deduce that Facebook had shown me ads on baby stuff, children's toys and home furnishings - and he was right. "In its most benign form, this profiling is used to show you targeted ads," he told me.</Para><Para>I also found out that it is easy for people to guess my daughter's school as a friend had named her school in a public post a few years ago.</Para><Para>ST_20180325_VNCAMBRIDGE_3860480.jpg</Para><Para>Related Story</Para><Para>Fallout from Facebook privacy scandal only just beginning</Para><Para>Related Story</Para><Para>Protecting your personal data from abuse</Para><Para>At least my address remained a secret as I am careful to never use the "check-in" function on Facebook, upload any pictures with location information or upload pictures of my home with recognisable landmarks.</Para><Para>Being inundated with targeted online ads is one thing, but Mr Flores said the mined data can, "as Cambridge Analytica has shown, be used to sell ideas and influence movements and politics".</Para><Para>For instance, a political manipulator can pay for ads to show me fake news with a headline that reads: "Government cannot fund you, turn to private donors instead, National Arts Council tells artists and musicians."</Para><Para>Said Mr Flores: "This headline is designed specifically to stir up emotions in you, based on your profile as a mother who is very much involved in your child's education."</Para><Para>Again, this was deduced from a public post which I was tagged to by a reader. In the post, the reader referred to an online commentary, "PSLE changes won't change Singapore's obsession with grades", that I had written in July 2016.</Para><Para>Contrary to belief, building a complete profile of a Facebook user who is not careful with his privacy settings is very easy.</Para><Para>For instance, it is extremely risky to upload pictures of your child in his school uniform with location details, or constantly click on the "check-in" feature on Facebook, as well as publicising your family holidays.</Para><Para>A stalker could familiarise himself with your movements and plan malicious acts, such as picking up your child without your knowledge, or breaking into your home when he could guess no one would be around.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Irene Tham </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

